    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:aecf1192-c30d-40ad-8457-606216e3eae8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old woman who appears well groomed and mildly overweight, with a habit of sitting forward slightly when describing the burning discomfort she feels after meals. She works as a project coordinator for a marketing firm, spending long hours at a desk and often eating lunch quickly between meetings. She reports frequent retrosternal burning, a sour taste in her mouth when lying down, and occasional nighttime cough, especially after late dinners or coffee. Although she is not in acute distress, she looks tired from interrupted sleep and says the symptoms have gradually become more bothersome over the past year.\n\nShe lives with her partner and two school-aged children and describes a busy household routine that often pushes dinner later into the evening. Her diet includes takeout meals several times a week, spicy foods, chocolate, and two to three cups of coffee per day. She drinks wine socially on weekends and does not smoke. She tries to stay active by taking weekend walks and attending an occasional yoga class, but she has not maintained a regular exercise routine since returning to full-time work after her second child.\n\nFriends and family describe {patientName} as dependable and energetic, though she admits she has become more irritable because of poor sleep and persistent throat irritation. She enjoys reading, short family trips, and gardening on weekends. She has started avoiding large meals before bed and sometimes props herself up with extra pillows, which gives partial relief. She is concerned because the symptoms are now affecting her concentration at work and her enjoyment of meals.\n\nOn casual observation, she has no signs of severe systemic illness, weight loss, or dehydration. Her voice is occasionally slightly hoarse in the morning, and she describes intermittent bloating after heavy meals. She remains independent in all activities of daily living and has strong family support, but her lifestyle patterns and meal timing clearly contribute to her symptom burden."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4a5543cb-4478-414c-b037-7b06e92e546c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had intermittent reflux symptoms for approximately 18 months, with increasing frequency over the last 6 months. She reports heartburn occurring 3 to 5 days per week, typically 30 to 60 minutes after meals and when reclining at night. Symptoms are triggered by tomato-based foods, coffee, chocolate, spicy meals, and late evening eating. Over-the-counter antacids provide temporary relief. She denies dysphagia, odynophagia, haematemesis, melena, or unintentional weight loss.\n\nHer past medical history is notable for mild obesity and seasonal allergic rhinitis. She has no known history of peptic ulcer disease, gallstones, chronic liver disease, or inflammatory bowel disease. She was hospitalized only for uncomplicated childbirths. She has never undergone upper gastrointestinal surgery. She reports moderate stress at work, inconsistent meal timing, and limited weekday physical activity. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol socially, usually 1 to 2 glasses of wine on weekends.\n\nShe takes cetirizine as needed during allergy season and occasionally uses ibuprofen for menstrual cramps or tension headaches. She drinks two to three coffees daily and often eats her evening meal within 2 hours of bedtime. Bowel habits are regular, and appetite is preserved. There is no personal history suggesting cardiac chest pain, and her symptoms are strongly meal- and position-related."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
